segments.text: Interview with Mr. B.A.
Anderson, side three.
I had difficulty in finding previous correspondence.
And it seems that all the correspondence was placed in a folder or folders, placed in the box and put up on the closet.
A year later, you didn't know what box contained what.
You didn't know where to look for anything.

So I realized that we needed to come to some standardization of material by the various departments then, I mean the police department and all the rest of them, and that file designations would be appropriate

so that, like you explained, if you wanted something, you know, a week or a month or five years from now, if you're looking for personnel or personnel matters, it would be in a personnel file, not a file with mechanics or, you know, any other function of the city.
So I proposed this scheme
But it met with a lot of resentment on the part of the city.
You know, people don't like to change.
And they were doing things one way, and they just didn't like it.
I also proposed at the same time the establishment of a library with a certain code.
I don't know whether you found it.
I think that's what I found, the code.
Well, I had two.
Oh, okay.
I had the library, you know, with the stuff that we wanted to file, plus the correspondence.
Okay.
So maybe I didn't see... Well, there were two.
And the library books were one thing, and then the...
I forgot what...
The library, I think I used the code of the...
I don't know now.
I think it was a regular library code, a Dewey Decimal adapted from something or other.
I know I spent a lot of time working that up and working the file system, because I wanted it for the file system particularly.
Because police matters shouldn't be put in a folder with administrative matters and then
The Parks Committee would be thrown in here and then put in a box.
You couldn't find anything.
So that's when, really, I started to save my own files.
Because if anything was important in order to protect myself, I had an extra copy made and put it in my file.
I can tell you about the 911 telephone that I had worked up.
And that's another thing that I'm
feather in my cap in a sense.
I'm glad to see that materialize.
But that, I forgot the year that was started and why.
Maybe that's when we started to have these problems.
I don't know the year.
Right.
But that was.
But see when
When the soup came along and all this, everything just died down.
And everybody lost those on the council.
They just lost interest.
They didn't have the interest that they did before.
Because you can't go gung-ho with that hanging over your head.
That's right.
feel that the city has gotten to a point where they really need to organize their records.
And this is probably one area that they will work on in the future.
And it's just a shame that it couldn't have been maintained.
Well, this is the thing that I asked a little while ago about the needs.
I could see that need.
And I could see these needs in the cemetery and this and this.
Because every time I looked around, I could see things that had to be done.
That's why I threw together that five-year plan myself and just sent it out to 100 people.
I know there was 100.
And I had them critique it and what's wrong with it.
Am I on the wrong track?
What else do you want?
What else do you think?
To get their reaction.
And I did it.
I got it.
But I'm sorry that never went through.
But I still think it's a good idea.
I do, too.
Also, we had valuable books there, publications in the library that you didn't know where they were.
At that time, we had the library in that back room.
They were just thrown together and stacked up, and if you wanted to go in and look for something special, they were just there.
Well, I couldn't tell you where they are now.
I haven't ever seen one place where they have a lot of books.
Were you also the first administration to work on a personnel manual?
Right.
Did you decide that the city needed it?
That was one of my babies.
Did you decide the city needed it?
I almost wrote all of that myself.
Or not wrote, I got it from, garnished it from other cities and everything else.
And we were beginning to grow up.
There was different regulations that abounded
annual leave and sick leave and some were leaving personnel off and there were problems.
Well, I understand that Joe got two days or four days for Christmas and how come I only got one?
You know, the city employees also came to him with all kinds of problems.
So that I knew, you know, I knew the workings pretty well in the city.
because they felt that they could come to me and talk to me.
Of course, I respected their opinion, but I wouldn't make any, you know, if they were wrong, they were wrong.
And, of course, I'd speak to the department and follow them, but at least I got their side of the story.
So until that point, the city employees never really, I don't know, organized?
We never had many regulations.
And what I was trying to do, I know it wasn't the best,
But what can I, you know what I mean?
I was working, too, with the university.
Right, that's right.
And I was given every available second to the city.
And I wrote most of that.
You know what I mean, or pulled it together.
Right.
Of course, I received a lot of criticism.
Why?
And I received it later, but...
I didn't see them do anything for the other cities had one if you wanted to know what's the vacation schedule for the year the council
You know, doing that.
Is it something that the council normally does?
Well, they set policies so that they'd say you get two days for Christmas or one for Thanksgiving or you get Fourth of July off or, you know, whatever it is.
So they have to approve it?
Yeah, they approve it by policy.
They just say this is a holiday schedule for the city.
A city manager...
And then, well, he has to abide by the policy.
Well, can he, or does it work where he formulates it in the city?
Well, he could, yeah.
In the city, okay.
Well, you know, in a way, then, Rand Boswell was a little weak as the city manager.
Well, I was going to ask you that.
I don't mean to, I don't want this into any of the records.
Okay.
But Rand was a little weak, and...
He didn't have much training in that.
He was manager of a bottling company before he came.
He served as a clerk.
And there's a lot more that's left unsaid.
But because of his weakness, I had to assume.
I overstepped myself in my role as mayor because I wanted to get things done.
I couldn't sit.
I wanted to move.
I wanted our city to move.
So you'll see that I kept implementing things all the time with things that normally should have come from him as a recommendation.
Well, was Langford then also a strong administrator, too?
Was that something that Mr. Boswell would do, too?
Well, see, they didn't have the things going as they did later on.
You know, the city didn't have that much to do.
We weren't growing that fast.
But more things were coming up every day.
You know what I mean?
We were trying to get the city, you know, in many ways, going.
And Rand was just not up to it.
I mean, he just didn't...
I respected him.
I thought a lot of him personally, but he wasn't a good administrator.
I know that I overstepped my bounds, but I just had to do it.
Things had to go.
I was ready to go.
I wasn't ready to sit.
I think my record substantially, I mean this weekly letter to the council on a Saturday tour of the whole city to answer any complaint from anybody on Sunday if necessary.
You know what I mean, it was my city.
Since I didn't have the opportunity to talk to Mr. Langford, I can only get from the records.
And he was mayor for quite a bit of time, but yet the city wasn't as big and things were not going on.
Well, they didn't have a problem.
And I think the minutes will reflect that.
That's right.
Because, you know, I was on the council with him.
Well, they were, I think maybe the most critical one was the page bill for the roads.
That came up before Joe Wood, and that was during his tenure at that point.
You know, this is out of sequence, but I meant to ask you, do you know why Mr. Langford decided to resign?
I mean, he had...
I've been the mayor for many years, but...
I think he just got to the point where he was getting pretty old.
Right.
He'd been retired from the university for at least 10 years.
And I thought, I think he was getting to the point where he just wanted to step down.
He just wanted to live up to it.
He enjoyed the honor because when he went to, like, league meetings, you know, he was always respected as the dean and
players, you know, for his team.
And he enjoyed that.
He enjoyed getting that.
But in his latter years, you know, he wasn't as active as he could be.
Okay.
We had been talking about the five-year plan.
This and the Browns' plan seemed to me to be what you had termed a forerunner to a comprehensive city plan.
And this happened after, this took effect after you were resigned, but the comprehensive, the 701 plan, do you know what I'm talking about?
Yeah, that came after.
Was it something that you worked on at all?
No, that...
I think that came after, and it was just really a follow-up, you know, stuff we were doing right along.
But most of the work on that 701 was done by others.
I want no credit for that.
And yet a lot of things in your plans, your five-year plans, were incorporated.
Oh, yeah.
And are even incorporated in the 22,000.
Yeah.
Well, that was really my own ideas, too, you know, that I just, you know, as you keep around in this field and that field and what they should be doing.
But Mr. Langford never really had a point in talking about music?
We've also talked about this earlier, too, but I found this very interesting, that during your administration, that College Station used federal funds for the first time, or applied for them.
And were you behind the effort?
Oh, yeah.
I was with Langford during his term.
We were all conservative, like I said earlier.
But then it soon became obvious to me, as well as to others, that all the communities surrounding us
College Station, Brine, and, you know, Hearn, and all the rest of them were getting funds, and we're just sitting here, and we're paying money out, and we're not getting anything in.
And even though we didn't like it, we might as well start getting a little bit in return, because we needed a sewer disposal plant, and if we could get 40%, why, it's too hard for us to do.
So if I remember, the sewer disposal plant was the first one that we, you know, it was the first federal project that we engaged in.
Was that the EDA doing it?
Yeah, yeah.
Were you able to complete that, the sewer system?
Yeah, yeah.
And the reason why I ask... Well, that's something else.
We found a baby down there one day.
Somebody came down through the fire.
Oh my gosh, you're kidding me.
We don't know.
It was examined by a doctor.
I don't know how long it was in the water and so on.
Probably some woman just got rid of it.
And no one ever reported it?
Oh yeah, it was reported.
I've seen some funny things, you know, sitting over there.
Well, was that mentioned in the paper?
They kept that out?
That's what I thought.
Oh my gosh.
That's just like building that water tower right down here.
I only wish they'd called me at that day.
They were going down with a lake at one of the towers, the tower at Watertown.
And that big...

drill that they were using i don't know how many feet down pretty deep well it dropped after we got down a certain distance and what happened it hit a pocket of sphagnum moss and everything else down there so they pulled it up well they found out the depth of that hole then pulled it up and of course sphagnum moss came up well i would have loved to
some of that moss and look at it under the microscope just to see what trees, what pollen, you know, everything about that particular moss.
But I didn't hear about it until the next day.
What they did, once they hit it, then under the contract they had to get out, I think, ten more feet.
And so they started to go beyond that hole.
But it's surprising to think that there's a big old
not a limestone cavern, but a cavern out there that had, you know, just full of moss.
You know, spaghid moss.
But I, the next day it was all dry and, you know, covered up.
What does that mean when you say spaghid?
Well, that means that in years past, or centuries past, during the upheaval, you know, the gulf, there used to be inland water.
that somehow or other this got in there, and I don't know.
But we could have looked at it through a microscope.
We might have been able to tell what plants were there, see?
What plants had been living at one time.
Right, in that hole.
In that hole.
Well, that's just a little...
You know, one of these things.
I get curious about things like that.
Oh, sure.
That's what makes life so interesting.
Yeah.
Okay, I was a little bit confused.
You had a bond election for water, and did you use that in connection with the EDA grant to build the sewer system and the water lines?
Well, we had a sewer grant and a water grant.
Oh, you had two separate ones.
And we extended our water line and then improved our sewer disposal system.
Actually, we enlarged the sewer disposal plant down there and put in a next room.
Yeah, where that bed, where that, I forget the name of it, where it comes up, the water comes up, and the animal life lives down there.
We put in another one of them.
And we improved the sewer lines in many parts of the city.
So we went ahead with these two things.
Okay.
After you left office, there was a grant, and it had to do with water and sewage, that was the government canceled on.
For some reason, I don't know.
Do you recall what I'm talking about?
No.
I don't know if it's in connection with this.
Sometimes it's hard to keep up with all the... Well, when I went out, I was just depressed.
For good reasons.
For many reasons, because, you know, I missed...
I lived in my city, and then, you know, to get out like I had to.
As you know, I went four months without a check.
Oh, well, I didn't realize it.
I realized that you stayed on longer than me.
And the wife finally told me one day, she said, I'm glad we went down long enough on principle.
And so I just had to get out.
Yeah.
I'm glad I did.
Of course, you were acquainted with the amendment that I worked on.
Oh, yes, yes.
I can't remember the 12.
12, I thought.
Well, everybody told me that I'd never succeed there, too.
I said, who are you to get an amendment passed, a constitutional amendment?
In Texas, people just, you know, turn them down and pass them.
And in the first place, you'll never get us through the legislature.
So I took that as a challenge.
Now, a lot of this is not written down either, but I formed a committee and, oh, what's his name, was it Brian Eagle?
He agreed to help me.
Oh, I formed a committee of about 12 people.
I did most of the work, though.
I don't think there's a university or college that I didn't like personally.
I must have spent close to maybe $1,000 of my own money getting a message out to student groups, organized labor, the blacks,
Anybody that I figured had anything to do.
A lot of people, people's positions were at stake.
Not only those that worked for the university, but they took the county agents that worked for irrigation districts.
In East Texas, they were on little boards way out in the rural areas of the state that were knocked out.
They couldn't serve.
They were the most knowledgeable people all throughout the state.

and I enlisted their support and well I knew enough about the legislature because I had served on the Texas Municipal League and various state committees and then before the legislature and I knew Ben Barnes and I knew Gus Mutcher and they've been just kicked out here you know but at that time I knew them all and I knew the procedures
And I knew who my friend mayors would be.
So we got the ball going.
I did get it through the legislature.
Was that hard?
Did you have any trouble?
Well, you had to know what to do and how to do it.
You know, who to see and what committees to go to.
It wasn't hard, but yet it wasn't easy.
You know.
So we got it through the legislature.
And I don't know that you know anything about legislating.
Oh, do I know anything?
Oh, it's, well, at any rate, I got it through the legislature.
And it was put up for constitutional ballot.
Then they told me .
That's really when I accepted another challenge.
And I was determined again.
I might be down in defeat, but then I'm going after him, and which I did.
And I sent out thousands of letters, and the Brine Eagle, this fellow from the Eagle, I forget his name now, he went from here to California.
And that brings up, well, that's a notice point, but the Brine Eagle.
But at any rate, this, he ran off something.
one-page, full-page eagle on both sides about this whole program.
And he provided me with all the copies I could use.
And I made one little appeal for money.
And I guess I took in about $150.
That's all.
Even I was surprised some people around here wouldn't donate one cent.
But then I didn't bother.
I was after something else.
There was a principal in there.
And so I started sending out these flyers.
And I don't think I missed a student college, student body, you know, a union.
I got that Texas Almanac out, and I mean, boy, I just, between this and my wife and another girl, I mean, boy, we sent letters out to everybody.
And when it came up for a vote, it just passed.
Now, it wasn't a high vote for it, but it passed.
And then we won.
And all of this now is over in the archives.
They were quite interested in it and wanted to be sure that they got it over.
Yes, sir.
I looked at that.
No, I still have some stuff in here.
to put in there when I, you know, someday in the future, when I get ready.
When sufficient time has passed.
Yeah.
I still got some stuff in my own pile.
And I got some other succulent stuff, too.
I'll hold that for now.
OK. We were talking about federal funds, and you mentioned the water and sewer funds.
Also, the HUD fund, is that right, that helped with providing housing for the, I guess, the lower class?
Yeah, yeah.
Well, at that, well, now the Catholic Church, you know, came in, but all I did was just support it.
It was their project.
Oh.
I don't understand that.
Oh, not housing development.
It was something like Southgate, then?
Yeah.
Southville?
Yeah, something like that.
That went in, and there was some objection there at the time.
And as far as I was concerned, I got with the bishop in Austin.
You know what I mean.
Again, I've tried to become knowledgeable on the subject one way or another.
And I was convinced that it would serve a good purpose to have it, at least having looked over what they had done over in Austin, too.
So I supported it.
There was some objection there, and they finally went through with it.
The one in Grime has not been a success at all.
I mean, they've had fights and murders and, you know, all kinds of problems in the Grime area.
Ours is still in effect?
Well, it was under the sponsorship of the Catholic Monastic Sync in Austin.
I don't know.
I think we had some place in the past where they sold that one.
I'm not sure.
They've had more.
These two were built about the same time.
Was it using HEV?
Yeah, I think it was.
And is it a subsidized rent?
Is that what it is?
Yeah.
Yeah.
OK. Also, in the area of transportation, I think you hinted at this before, but the city applied for federal funds through the topics plan.
Is that right?
Yeah.
But I don't think we ever got anything.
I didn't meet another one.
Was that for signalization?
Yeah.
Oh, okay.
Yeah.
That was pretty, now the highway department was handling that.
I know they had to approve everything.
Yeah, they were the ones that were allocated the money, as I recall, to dish out.
I'm not sure, maybe we did, but I'm not sure.
I'm not sure.
Well, as I was reading the minutes, I may have extended past your term as mayor, and they signalized the lights maybe right after you resigned, is that?
Maybe, could be.
Or maybe, I just forget.
Well, I do remember there was...
in the minutes and talked about Joe Hanna coming on, if he could.
Yeah, he was District Engineer, yeah.

And at first, College Station turned down funds to have their lights signaled because they were upset that, I think, like, only one light or two lights were going to be signalized, whereas in Bryan, they had a whole school of lights.
Yeah.
They didn't think it was proportionately fair.
And then Mr. Hanover came to talk to them, and I believe they had the signal.
Yeah.
I forgot.
All right.
Thank you.
Maybe so.
You know, some of these things are a little hazy now.
All right.
Also, another one that, another project that I found real interesting is the Rubber Street project.
Do you remember?
Oh, yeah, that rubber and glass?
Mm-hmm.
Yeah.
Well, you know, that was just some other innovative thing, and that was, I forget his name, that ground-up rubber, and...
We had a few streets, well, they're still messed up.
From an engineering standpoint, they weren't put in properly.
And the minutes will reflect, I think, where I objected to it at the time.
This was when we had that pay as you go.
And this developer wanted to put in
concrete streets.
That's way back.
And he wanted to put it on clay without reinforcing.
And if you'll notice, I objected to this procedure because I didn't think that the concrete would hold together on clay and bounce around.
Yeah, it's fine.
And I was assured by some engineer that you don't know what you're talking about.
You're not an engineer, highway engineer, and you don't know anything about concrete.
And at any rate, White, it was agreed that he could go ahead and put five inches of concrete on top of Clay.
Well, the end result is as you see it back there.
Do you ever drive in that?
What street?
Oh, Westover and all that area down there.
And there were huge cracks and everything else.
Well, this seemed then, there was one street, this seemed like a good opportunity to take one of these streets and try this rubber and glass.
I think it was glass, too, wasn't it?
Or was it just rubber?
I don't know.
Well, sometimes it was a, let's put it in the name of a stretch.
It was a mixture of ground and tires.
Yeah.
So we, and then this fellow from the university, and he was, his reputation was on the line, and you know, PhD, and he seemed to know, you know, had highway experience.
It was with TTI.

so we agreed to go ahead and let's try this stuff out so we tried it and we didn't have two months or he didn't have two months success in laying he had some problems with the machine but uh be that as it may why we finally put it on a screen or two up there
And it never really, it never really found out.
It didn't?
No, no.
Were you using federal funds to?
Yeah, I think we did have, he had, yeah.
It was his project primarily.
But you allowed him to go ahead and use.
Oh yeah, yeah.
But the project paper really didn't work out.
No.
It sounded like such a good idea.
Yeah, well it did to us too, you know, and you're grabbing at straws because
You had an area like that.
The only other alternative was to tear up the whole street and redo it.
Now, instead of putting that concrete on clay, if they had come along and put gravel or sand to cushion it, see, and let it move, and let it move back and forth and up and down, they didn't do it.
And I think you find in the minutes where I did object, I always said that.
They told me I didn't have any sense and I didn't know what I was talking about.
You didn't have the background to answer that question.
Yeah, so that was an interesting little project.
In the area of recreation, as I understand it, you were very active in obtaining undeveloped land for parks.
Well, I was trying to, yeah.
I started this matter while I was mayor where we had that ordinance that provided that a certain piece of that land had to go, or its equivalent in money, had to go for parks.
From developers?
Yeah.
And I remember that ordinance specifically and worked hard for its adoption.
At the time, I recall, we said it was unconstitutional and this, that, and the other, but other cities were playing it.
So we passed it.
And I think it was very fortunate because it enabled us at least to get little pieces of land to get the park system started.
And that five year plan, didn't I have a large park of 100 acres?
I forgot now what it was.
I don't know what one thing, too, that isn't in the record, I don't think, is this.
A&M used to get franchise tax from telephone use.
And let's see, was it Dick Gilchrist as chancellor?
I was always trying to get money from every possible source.
The university was picking up, as I recall, about $4,000 or $5,000 a year out of a telephone franchise tax.
That, in other cities, was going to the city.
So I communicated with all cities in Texas that had a university in connection with it and determined that the franchise tax was going to the city, not the university.
So I approached the university and they fought me on that, the university did.
But we always had an understanding there.
After it was all over, we won.
Oh, you got franchised?
Yeah.
I really got a GTE and a buying because they knew Rudder and they were personal friends, you know, the president.
And he didn't want anything to do to a fan Rudder.
But I got him such a legal ground that he couldn't refuse but write me eventually.
and tell me that we have the right to the tax.
So we picked up that tax, which in that day and time was a lot of money.
When you were, did you try to establish, well, let me see if I can phrase this right.
It seems as though in your administration that the city,
decided that there was a need for parkland.
Is that a correct statement?
Oh, yeah, it is.
The council, we all agreed that we needed more parkland.
And it was a matter of how we could get it.
We had no people of wealth in our community.
Like in Bryan, there were some people of wealth in years gone past, you know, that could donate land.

but nothing like that in college and most of them worked for the university retired from the university so we needed more parkland to be sure but how do we get it and this idea of getting it through the real estate people or the developers it wasn't new because other cities had been doing it
So we decided to approach this angle to get some of this parking.
And we really didn't have too much money to go out and, you know, go out and buy it.

Now we did do some investigating with the possibility of getting some federal funds, at least I did, because I had some Salt Conservation people and others come in to look over different tracks with this in mind.
But nothing developed.
Our heart was in it, but we never got around to doing it.
Of course, I forget now the time and the events and the plays and things like this.
Was Boyette against this developer dedication?
I think this came after him.
Yeah, I know it did.
It came after him.
Yeah, we were interested in parks because, see, they went with me, for example, on the Lincoln Center.
Reluctantly.
But they didn't.
At that time, of course, we had, what, three centers of Negro activity.
Now we only have maybe two, and they really don't amount to much anymore.
But, you know, we used to have a larger population.
Oh, really?
How did the change to

change to the council at large voting council council members at large come about instead of the lord's system well we figured at a time that we'd have a more representative government if everyone had an opportunity for everybody that went on the council
We've got to consider that the wards, the early wards at least, were such that, like I said, we'd have maybe 15 or 20 people vote in one ward and 160 vote in another.
and there was no equity when they got to the council table.
The one that had represented 20 people had as much, only as much authority, and the one representing six times as much only had the same voting purpose.
So we, you know, was kicking around the idea that it might be better to have voting at large and to
You know, everybody then would have a chance to, you know, name who they wanted the city council.
And this is done, or had been done, in some areas.
Subsequently, if I recall, the Supreme Court came along and said that this was
Oh, we don't have it today?
I don't think so.
I don't know of a Texas city that... What is ours considered a place system?
Yeah, place.
You decide what place you...
It's not necessarily where you live.
It's just... Is that right?
Yeah, that's right.
And everybody can vote for you for that place?
For that place, yeah.
But I...
In the essential, I'm the same thing.
I don't know.
I haven't heard any comments of late about our system.
But I know in the early days, you know, that it just went one way and then the other.
And the days before, boy, yeah, you know, that was a problem.
When he would be elected from Ward 3 with only a handful of votes, don't you mean?
Yeah, well, I know one of them went in with 12 votes.
Oh, really?
Yeah, for the council.
And I went in here with about 120 votes.
And somebody over in the south side would go in and say it was 210.
And he couldn't have as much to say with 12 volts.
And, you know, the two of us combined had, what, 40 times more than he did.
So, you know, it caused people to sit up and take notice.
And, well, it just went one way then the other.
Were you, were you one of the people who pushed for the change?
Oh yeah, when I had a lot of this inequity, yeah.
And then particularly with Boyette, and then my inability to get anything done.
I wanted something done, we had to move.
That's just like even cooperating with the university, putting lights on the west side of the campus.
